n how=\r\n we play our allotted roles. \n\nThe role you are given is your destiny and h=\r\now you play it is your free will. How you play your role now (free will) in=\r\nfluences what role you are given in future (destiny).\n\nIf the role given to=\r\n you (e.g. Arjuna) is to kill your guru (Drona) and relatives, you cannot e=\r\nscape it. But you can either do it with a hateful mind or a guilty mind or =\r\nyou can do it with a calm mind. If the role given to you (e.g. Janaka) is t=\r\no rule a big kingdom, you cannot escape and do penances in a forest. But yo=\r\nu can either rule the kingdom with a proud and attached mind or with a calm=\r\n mind. If the role given to you (e.g. Swami Samarth Ramadas) is to guide a =\r\nmighty king (Shivaji) in resisting the invading muslim\n kings, you cannot e=\r\nscape it. But you can either do it with an attached and agitated mind or a =\r\ncalm mind.\n\nPeople in the examples I mentioned above engaged in what may se=\r\nem like material actions, but they did them after overcoming attachments an=\r\nd with an equanimous mind.\n\nAs I keep saying, what you do is a secondary fa=\r\nctor and how you do it is primary. Even as we engage in actions that we bel=\r\nieve to be our dharma, we should work on our attitude and increase surrende=\r\nr. When one has surrendered to god and is able to look at pleasure and pain=\r\n, praise and censure in the same way, then one&#39;s dharma will be far clearer=\r\n to one. One whose mind is densely conditioned by duality and desires will =\r\nsee one&#39;s dharma through the coloring of that conditioning and may misjudge=\r\n. On the other hand, one with a clear mind with very little conditioning wi=\r\nll see one&#39;s dharma clearer.\n\nIn simpler words, one who heavily identifies =\r\nwith the body and wants\n comforts and pleasures of the body will see one&#39;s =\r\ndharma from that motivation. One may identify with body, with a group of pe=\r\nople, with a deity etc. As is the identification, so is the conditioning an=\r\nd so is one&#39;s vision of one&#39;s dharma.\n\nThough everyone is playing their all=\r\notted role, some have densely conditioned minds and unable to see their dha=\r\nrma clearly and pursuing adharma. As a result, they may continue to be allo=\r\ntted roles where densely conditioned minds restrict their actions, in futur=\r\ne.\n\nSome have very clear minds and able to see their dharma clearly and pur=\r\nsuing higher dharma. As a result, they may continue to allotted roles where=\r\n lighter and lighter mental conditioning restricts them and eventually they=\r\n become free.\n\nOne can try to use free will to move from the former case to=\r\n the latter case.\n\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n------------ --------- ---------=\r\n --------- --------- --------- --------- -\n=C2=A0 Free Jyotish\n Software, F=\r\nree Jyotish Lessons, Jyotish Writings,\n&quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for =\r\nshort Homam and Pitri Tarpana:\n=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =\r\n=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 http://www.VedicAst rologer.org\n=C2=A0 =C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0Films that make a difference: http://SaraswatiFil ms.org\n=C2=A0 =C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0Spirituality: http://groups. yahoo.com/ group/vedic- wisdom\n=C2=\r\n=A0 Jyotish writings: http://groups. yahoo.com/ group/JyotishWri tings\n----=\r\n-------- --------- --------- --------- --------- --------- --------- -\n\n---=\r\n- Raj Nambisan &lt;rajnambisan@ yahoo.com&gt;\n wrote: \n&gt; namaste,\n&gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt; i ha=\r\nve a question: if everyone is playing the allotted role, as the peerless ma=\r\nharshi alludes to, then what&#39;s the point in our debating these things? \n&gt;=\r\n=C2=A0 \n&gt; wouldn&#39;t the thesis apply to osama, nehru, gandhiji equally -- th=\r\nat is, each one is/was playing the exact role he is/was supposed to, right =\r\nor wrong?\n&gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt; which begs the question, when does free will begin and=\r\n fate end?\n&gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt; enlightenment, pl